// @proven: 1
// @failed: 0
// @unknown: 1
// Soundness: an overflow inside the solver must never be reported as a proof.
//
// std/smt decides feasibility by Fourier-Motzkin elimination, which multiplies constraint
// constants together. A bound near 2^62 overflows i64 on the first combine; at -O2 that
// wraps, the row's sign flips, the system looks infeasible, and the old code reported
// UNSAT — i.e. **proven**. Verified against z3, which says sat: `x = -1` satisfies
//   (>= x -4611686018427387904) & (<= x 4611686018427387904) & (not (>= x 0))
// so `half(x)` here really can be called with a negative n. A false proof is the worst
// answer a prover can give — worse than no answer — so combine() now detects the overflow
// and the verdict degrades to `unknown`.
//
// (The 1 proven is main's own call, buggy(10) — a constant that satisfies the bound.)
// This asserts the DEGRADATION, not a proof: if someone widens the solver's arithmetic
// later, this becomes `failed` (with x = -1) and the annotation should follow. What must
// never come back is `proven`.
pub fn half(n: i64): i64
requires n >= 0
{
    return n / 2
}

pub fn buggy(x: i64): i64
requires x >= 0 - 4611686018427387904 && x <= 4611686018427387904
{
    return half(x)
}

pub fn main() {
    print(buggy(10))
}
